</div></div><a id="comment-256"></a>
<article class="comment comment-by-anonymous even clearfix" about="/comment/256#comment-256" typeof="sioc:Post sioct:Comment">

  <header>
    <p class="submitted">
            <span property="dc:date dc:created" content="2015-05-22T15:41:51+10:00" datatype="xsd:dateTime" rel="sioc:has_creator"><span class="username" xml:lang="" typeof="sioc:UserAccount" property="foaf:name" datatype="">Anonymous</span> replied on <time pubdate datetime="2015-05-22T15:41:51+10:00">Fri, 2015-05-22 15:41</time></span>      <a href="/comment/256#comment-256" class="permalink" rel="bookmark">Permalink</a>    </p>

            
      </header>

  <span rel="sioc:reply_of" resource="/blog/putting-user-centre-everything" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span><div class="field field-name-comment-body field-type-text-long field-label-inline clearfix"><div class="field-label">Comment:&nbsp;</div><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="content:encoded"><p>Putting the user at the &quot;centre of everything&quot; needs to start with legislation/policy.</p>
<p>Here&#039;s one example. Yesterday, I received a letter in the post from Medicare. It explained that my family had reached the threshold for the Medicare Safety Net as we&#039;d spent a certain amount on healthcare costs so far this year and that we may be eligible for a higher Medicare benefit for the remainder of the year. The letter contained a summary of information about my family including our Medicare card number and all of our names. It also said that in order to be eligible for the higher Medicare benefit we had to fill out a form to confirm that our family composition hadn&#039;t changed. A paper form was enclosed in the envelope. It was a blank standard form with fields to write (with a pen) our Medicare card number, names etc. There was no option to tick a box to say &#039;the details you&#039;ve got are still accurate&#039;. Nor was there any mention on the form or in the letter of an alternative way of confirming that our details remain the same.</p>
<p>I was bewildered by this process. Why on earth would I be required to fill our a paper form to inform Medicare that the details they&#039;ve already got (and that they printed in the letter to me) were still correct? As a &#039;user&#039; this seems nuts. So I called Medicare to ask about it.</p>
<p>It turns out that the process is done this way because the Health Insurance Act says it must be:</p>
<p>Specifically, section 10AE Confirmation of family composition states:</p>
<p>&quot;If the Chief Executive Medicare is satisfied that...a registered family would be...entitled to increased benefits..., the Chief Executive Medicare must request that the person who registered the family or another family member state, in a manner approved by the Chief Executive Medicare, whether or not...the composition of the family remains...as originally registered&quot;</p>
<p>And that &quot;Until a family member provides the information...increased benefits are not payable&quot;.</p>
<p>So, the legislation requires that before an increased benefit can be paid I have to complete a form to indicate that the details Medicare has recorded are still up-to-date. This isn&#039;t very user-centric. </p>
<p>Presumably, the reason this is required is to deal with the possibility that the composition of our family may have changed (due to divorce, death, etc) and that if we were to automatically receive an increased benefit it might be paid in error. Clearly this policy exists to ensure the Commonwealth does not pay higher Medicare benefits to families that are no longer eligible for them. It puts an impost on everyone who might be eligible for increased benefits to:</p>
<p>- write down the details Medicare already has on record with a pen on a piece of paper<br />
- purchase an envelope and stamp<br />
- post the letter</p>
<p>I&#039;d be interested to know how many people&#039;s family composition changes and how many people&#039;s family composition remains the same. Given that a family can potentially reach the Safety Net Threshold each year and family-composition-changing events probably don&#039;t happen each year then there may well be more cases where the family composition remains unchanged.</p>
<p>I wonder how many people who are eligible for an increased Medicare Benefit never receive it because they fail to complete and return the form.</p>
<p>Clearly, this process is ripe for being &#039;digitally transformed&#039;. I&#039;m sure we can all think of ways to simplify the completion of the form. But, the point of this story is that thinking of how an existing process can be made &#039;user centric&#039; is only the first step. We&#039;ll be genuinely putting people at the centre of everything when we ensure policies and legislation are drafted with the needs of people in mind rather than focusing solely on the need to ensure benefits aren&#039;t inadvertently given to people who aren&#039;t eligible.</p>
</div></div></div>
  
