  <header>
    <p class="submitted">
            <span property="dc:date dc:created" content="2015-05-26T10:55:38+10:00" datatype="xsd:dateTime" rel="sioc:has_creator"><span class="username" xml:lang="" typeof="sioc:UserAccount" property="foaf:name" datatype="">Jacqui</span> replied on <time pubdate datetime="2015-05-26T10:55:38+10:00">Tue, 2015-05-26 10:55</time></span>      <a href="/comment/306#comment-306" class="permalink" rel="bookmark">Permalink</a>    </p>

            
      </header>

  <span rel="sioc:reply_of" resource="/blog/putting-user-centre-everything" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span><div class="field field-name-comment-body field-type-text-long field-label-inline clearfix"><div class="field-label">Comment:&nbsp;</div><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="content:encoded"><p>My 80 year old mother has the Centrelink app on her phone, and loves being able to received mail and check her pension online. However, the written instructions that were mailed to my mother were useless, she rang Centrelink and the staff had no idea how to assist my mother in installing the app or connecting her account.  Finally she went to her local Centrelink office, waited in line and recevied assistance. </p>
<p>There is perhaps an assumption that older folk are incapable or dislike doing business online, when quite possibly it is just a lack of digital literacy. Not just in clients trying to access a digital service, but those frontline government staff deliverying the service. </p>
<p>No matter what the delivery channel; digital, face-to-face or paper, everyone just wants to be able to access the right information, at the right time, in a format they can understand.</p>
<p>Also, more money for public libraries.</p>
